{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_21","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"cat <<'EOF' > /home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/apple-hig-research.md\n# Apple HIG Research\n\n## Source Policy\n- Source policy follows Apple primary guidance only for interaction, motion, accessibility, notification behavior, and platform conventions.\n- Secondary sources are used only to resolve exact Apple URLs and were not used for authoritative interpretation.\n- This artifact intentionally avoids any proprietary screenshots, exact competitor layouts, and private business-sensitive copy.\n- No secrets, credentials, tokens, cookies, private keys, session values, or environment variables are included.\n\n## Source List\n- [Apple Human Interface Guidelines](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/?locale=en_us)\n- [Designing for iOS](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/designing-for-ios)\n- [Onboarding](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/onboarding)\n- [Tab bars](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/tab-bars)\n- [Navigation and search](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/navigation-and-search)\n- [Buttons](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons)\n- [Lists and tables](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/lists-and-tables)\n- [Labels](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/labels)\n- [Alerts](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/alerts)\n- [Accessibility](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/accessibility)\n- [Notifications](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/notifications)\n- [Managing notifications](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/managing-notifications)\n- [Motion](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/motion)\n- [Privacy](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/privacy)\n- [UserNotifications framework](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/UserNotifications)\n- [Request permission to use notifications](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/usernotifications/asking_permission_to_use_notifications?changes=latest____8_8&language=objc)\n- [SwiftUI accessibility modifiers](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/swiftui/view-accessibility)\n\n## Applicable HIG Constraints\n- Onboarding should be fast, optional, and ideally occur after launch completion, so first launch should not feel blocked by setup; WakeTask implication: keep launch path short, make onboarding skippable, and keep task-value visible early.\n- Onboarding guidance is strongest when people can test interactions directly; implication: convert long instructional copy into one-action mini interactions for wake setup and reminder creation.\n- Tab bars are for top-level navigation, must be stable across sections, and should include clear labels; implication: keep \"'`MainTabView` to 3 primary shells, keep labels specific (`Home`, `Runs`, `Profile`), and avoid moving tabs based on workflow state.\n- Tab bars should stay visible during normal area switches; implication: avoid hiding the tab bar during routine wake management paths unless entering system modal contexts.\n- Buttons should have clear roles and avoid mixed visual weight; implication: each wake or paywall screen should expose one dominant action with one clear secondary action.\n- Button hit target guidance requires generous touch area (`44x44` minimum); implication: increase tappable surfaces for list controls and time-critical action controls in active wake and completion screens.\n- Lists and tables should keep row text succinct and readable; implication: simplify home/run list rows into title + short status line with clear disclosure for deeper detail.\n- Use disclosure patterns for navigation rather than overloading information controls; implication: move “info” row behaviors toward explicit drill-down flows for settings and history details.\n- Alerts must be used sparingly, have clear titles/messages, and present only essential actions; implication: reserve alerts for destructive confirmations and mission-critical interruption decisions, not routine reminders.\n- Accessibility in HIG requires intuitive, perceivable, and adaptable interfaces; implication: ensure VoiceOver labels, semantic ordering, and Dynamic Type-friendly typography in onboarding, wake controls, and profile/legal actions.\n- Notification permissions should request only required interaction types and be contextually introduced; implication: request in an explanatory pre-alert step before scheduling wake reminders, not at first app launch.\n- Motion should communicate status and cause/effect and be intentionally restrained; implication: keep wake transitions short, meaning-rich, and avoid decorative motion loops in urgent completion/recovery states.\n\n## Interaction And Motion Guidance\n- Use a progressive interaction model in onboarding and creation flows: teach a step, let users test it, then advance.\n- Keep navigation patterns consistent with iOS conventions: modal for focused decisions, navigation stacks for multi-level task flow, and tabs for horizontal area changes.\n- For active wake execution, prefer a single dominant action to reduce cognitive burden while mission status is changing.\n- In active or failure-recovery states, use minimal transitions to communicate next step quickly rather than extra micro-interactions.\n- Add explicit state and progress messaging for asynchronous operations (loading, scheduling, sending, completion) to avoid perceived hangs.\n- Respect motion preferences: if your app exposes custom animation, make sure non-action-critical flows can run with reduced motion expectations.\n- Keep copy actionable and short around motion-triggered transitions to minimize ambiguity during high-stakes wake states.\n\n## Accessibility Guidance\n- Apple’s accessibility model requires interfaces that are intuitive, perceivable, and adaptable; WakeTask should not depend on a single sensory channel for task outcomes.\n- SwiftUI provides built-in accessibility defaults but custom views still need explicit labels and values; use `.accessibilityLabel(_:)`, `.accessibilityHint(_:)`, and `.accessibilityValue(_:)` on custom controls.\n- Support dynamic type and readable hierarchy in labels and row text, and avoid relying on only color semantics for status and error states.\n- Ensure custom list rows and controls have a clear accessible element model so screen readers can move in task order without dead-ends.\n- For interactive elements, keep sufficient spacing and target size, especially in bottom action zones and row action controls.\n- For success/error states in wake flow and completion screens, announce state changes in a short, structured way to avoid silent transitions.\n\n## Notification And Interruption Guidance\n- Notification interactions should be permission-gated and context-aware; request authorization only for interaction options actually used (`alert`, `sound`, `badge`).\n- The HIG framing is consistent: use notifications for important information that should break out of foreground flow, and use in-context UI for routine status info.\n- Avoid starting users in alert-heavy experiences; do not place startup-like blocking notifications or alerts before onboarding and core task visibility.\n- Actionable notifications should focus on high-value actions and simple reply/acknowledge choices where appropriate.\n- Because notification delivery is not guaranteed even with setup, design resilient state in the app that tolerates missed delivery without alarming language.\n- Use respectful timing and interruption strategy for streak/recovery messaging; avoid repeated or escalating prompts after each miss.\n\n## Screen Type Implications\n- Onboarding: make onboarding optional and resumable, shorten content density, and lead users directly to first useful action.\n- Home: present clear, top-level mission state first, then secondary support tiles, because users should see what to do next in one scan.\n- Primary list: use list semantics with succinct rows and readable status chips, with explicit sorting/filter controls grouped behind navigation actions.\n- Create/edit: reduce choice overload by sequencing fields, validating progressively, and keeping destructive actions separated from primary create flow.\n- Active task: keep one primary action visible, keep control count low, and show deterministic progress and remaining steps.\n- Completion: provide direct feedback, explicit “done / retry / defer” options, and avoid guilt language when a task is missed.\n- History/streaks: make definitions explicit (`what counts`, `what does not`), keep trends compact, and avoid alarmist messaging.\n- Profile/settings: separate operational account tasks (sign-out, delete account, legal) from wake mission actions and add confirmation for destructive paths.\n- Paywall/subscription: place paywall as explicit feature boundary, not as an interruption during active task or completion-critical moments.\n\n## what_to_adapt\n- Use tab-based top-level navigation with stable `TabView` behavior and clear labels that describe function, not feature names.\n- Use SwiftUI-native composition for onboarding (`TabView` or paging cards) with clear progress and skip/continue controls.\n- Use explicit primary/secondary button styling to preserve decision clarity, with one dominant action in wake-critical states.\n- Use `List` and `NavigationStack` to preserve hierarchical clarity between list summaries and detail/edit states.\n- Adopt accessibility-first SwiftUI defaults and add explicit `accessibilityLabel`, `accessibilityValue`, and `accessibilityHint` on custom components.\n- Make notifications and alerts explicit by context: ask for permission before scheduling wake reminders, and use minimal actionable notification categories.\n- Keep motion for wake and completion transitions functional and short, with reduced-motion resilience in timing-sensitive screens.\n\n## what_not_to_copy\n- Do not require mandatory onboarding before any useful context is available.\n- Do not use tab bars as action rows or hide section tabs unpredictably across flow states.\n- Do not crowd wake or completion screens with equal-emphasis buttons; avoid ambiguous primary actions.\n- Do not use alerts for pure information; use in-screen explanatory states for non-critical notices.\n- Do not copy competitor or template color/spacing systems that reduce touch target size below platform expectations.\n- Do not queue repetitive interruption prompts (notifications/alerts/overlays) after one miss or failed wake attempt.\n- Do not expose destructive settings (account deletion, paywall escalation, reset) with low-clarity copy or insufficient confirmation.\n- Do not depend on exact visual parity with iOS defaults if accessibility, voice order, or dynamic type can degrade the interaction path.\nEOF'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
