{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_26","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"bash -lc \\\"mkdir -p /home/daytona/workspace/.fabro/scratch/01KRSF5GBPG07T76DS9X1PJX8S/parallel/research_fanout/apple_hig_research/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research && cat <<'EOF' > /home/daytona/workspace/.fabro/scratch/01KRSF5GBPG07T76DS9X1PJX8S/parallel/research_fanout/apple_hig_research/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/apple-hig-research.md\n# Apple HIG Research\n\n## Source Policy\n- Source policy follows Apple primary guidance only for interaction, motion, accessibility, notification behavior, and platform conventions.\n- Secondary sources are used only to resolve exact Apple URLs and were not used for authoritative design claims.\n- This artifact avoids any proprietary screen copy, private design assets, or sensitive credentials.\n- No secrets, API keys, tokens, cookies, private keys, session values, or environment variables are included.\n\n## Source List\n- [Apple Human Interface Guidelines](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/?locale=en_us)\n- [Designing for iOS](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/designing-for-ios)\n- [Onboarding](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/onboarding)\n- [Tab bars](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/tab-bars)\n- [Navigation and search](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/navigation-and-search)\n- [Buttons](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/buttons)\n- [Lists and tables](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/lists-and-tables)\n- [Labels](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/labels)\n- [Alerts](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/alerts)\n- [Accessibility](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/accessibility)\n- [Notifications](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/notifications)\n- [Managing notifications](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/managing-notifications)\n- [Motion](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/motion)\n- [Privacy](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/privacy)\n- [UserNotifications framework](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/UserNotifications)\n- [Ask permission to use notifications](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/usernotifications/asking_permission_to_use_notifications?changes=latest____8_8&language=objc)\n- [SwiftUI accessibility modifiers](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/swiftui/view-accessibility)\n\n## Applicable HIG Constraints\n- Onboarding should be optional where possible and placed after launch is complete; implication: don’t gate launch on full setup, and keep first-run paths short with a clear continue/skip decision so users can reach value quickly.\n- Onboarding should teach through interactivity; implication: replace static onboarding copy with one interactive confirmation at a time, especially for wake-plan defaults and reminders.\n- Tab bars should support navigation, not actions, and should remain visible and predictable across section switches; implication: keep \"'`MainTabView` for stable section boundaries and keep tab order/titles stable (`Home`, `Runs`, `Profile`).\n- Buttons should present clear roles and one dominant call to action where possible; implication: in active-task and completion screens, avoid multiple equal-weight controls competing for attention.\n- Button touch targets should be comfortably hittable (44x44 guidance on iOS); implication: increase tappable area on run controls, quick action cards, and destructive actions.\n- Lists should use succinct row content and clear navigation affordances; implication: simplify Home/Wake lists into short title-status rows with explicit drill-down indicators.\n- Alerts should be reserved for critical actions and should be neutral and direct; implication: do not use alerts for routine status info or non-essential confirmation prompts.\n- Accessibility is core behavior (intuitive, perceivable, adaptable); implication: ensure controls are named, ordered, and legible under Dynamic Type across wake and history screens.\n- Notification authorization should be explicit and limited to needed types; implication: request permission only with options the app uses and in a context that explains wake reminder value.\n- Motion should communicate change and state, not entertain; implication: keep active-task transitions concise and avoid decorative animation loops around urgency screens.\n- HIG and iOS conventions assume brief interruption handling; implication: avoid startup modal or push-heavy interrupt patterns before core task context is established.\n\n## Interaction And Motion Guidance\n- Maintain task momentum with predictable progression: onboarding slides → home visibility → primary wake setup → execution → completion.\n- Keep interaction density low during high urgency moments (active wake), then expand controls in low-stakes review states.\n- Use state-specific primary actions and clear status language; avoid ambiguous “maybe next” buttons.\n- For lists, cards, and quick actions, use consistent spacing and grouping so users scan in one glance.\n- Add motion only when it encodes a state transition (for example, start, complete, skip, retry) and avoid persistent background motion in mission-critical screens.\n- Preserve interruption safety by making transitions reversible where possible and by confirming destructive actions clearly.\n\n## Accessibility Guidance\n- Use built-in accessibility defaults in SwiftUI and explicitly annotate custom controls with labels, hints, and values where semantics are not obvious.\n- Ensure text hierarchy stays legible under Dynamic Type and don’t rely on color alone to show enabled/disabled or success/fail state.\n- For active wake and completion flows, provide explicit spoken state updates via value/label patterns so assistive technologies receive clear outcome feedback.\n- Keep control grouping and reading order aligned with task sequence: task start, status, secondary action, help.\n- For lists and legal/settings screens, avoid unlabeled controls and dense icon-only actions unless supported by system conventions.\n- Where sound is used for success/error feedback, pair with non-audio confirmation paths to remain inclusive.\n\n## Notification And Interruption Guidance\n- Request notification permissions only in context and only after explaining why reminders/replies are useful for wake routines.\n- Use `UNUserNotificationCenter` authorization with only required options (`alert`, `sound`, `badge`) matching actual behavior.\n- Use alerts and notifications for meaningful interruption events, not purely informational updates that can be surfaced in-app.\n- Design for missed or delayed delivery as an edge case rather than failure; keep app state resilient when a reminder does not arrive.\n- Prefer action-based notification categories for high-value, response-oriented notifications; keep interaction choices small and legible.\n- Avoid repeated interruption patterns after each failure event; provide recovery controls in-app before suggesting another push.\n\n## Screen Type Implications\n- Onboarding: show concise purpose + optional path, allow exit/skip and resume, and avoid launching into rigid data collection.\n- Home: expose primary mission signal first (next wake action, active state), then secondary cards.\n- Primary_list (wake run list): prioritize row clarity and short status text, keep list scanning fast on first launch and under one-hand use.\n- Create_edit: stage form steps, validate progressively, keep save/confirm as the dominant action and support quick cancellation.\n- Active_task: treat as urgency state; show one clear control for mission action and clearly labeled recovery/finish path.\n- Completion: present success confirmation, emotional continuity, and optional replay/recover options without shaming.\n- History_streaks: explain metrics in plain language so users understand how streaks are computed and repaired.\n- Profile_settings: separate account/help/legal/support from mission controls; protect destructive actions with explicit confirmation.\n- Paywall_subscription: keep paywall presentation contextual and not as an interruption mid-mission; maintain transparent opt-out and restore paths.\n\n## what_to_adapt\n- Use system-first SwiftUI structures for navigation (`NavigationStack`, `List`, `TabView`) and keep customizations minimal.\n- Use explicit onboarding progression with optionality and short explanatory copy tied to immediate app actions.\n- Keep tab navigation at the top level and keep every tab icon/label singular and descriptive.\n- Use one dominant button style for the primary action and secondary styling for alternative options.\n- Add explicit accessibility labels/hints/values to custom controls and keep action feedback accessible in text.\n- Implement notification requests in a clearly-scoped prelude to reminder features, and align notification actions with wake mission outcomes.\n- Use motion for task status and completion feedback only; keep high-frequency animations short and interruptible.\n\n## what_not_to_copy\n- Do not copy closed-loop onboarding that blocks launch or requires full auth completion before value becomes visible.\n- Do not copy layouts where tab bars behave like action rails or change visibility unpredictably.\n- Do not copy alert-heavy patterns for non-critical flow messaging.\n- Do not copy dense equal-weight CTA sets during active wake and completion states.\n- Do not copy color-only status systems or tiny control targets that reduce operability with accessibility settings.\n- Do not copy repetitive interruption behavior (repeat alerts/push loops) after missed wake attempts.\n- Do not copy platform-incompatible wording or tone in destructive paths (especially in profile/legal account actions).\n- Do not copy inaccessible custom controls lacking SwiftUI accessibility annotations.\nEOF\"'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
