mpletion flows, provide explicit spoken state updates via value/label patterns so assistive technologies receive clear outcome feedback.\n- Keep control grouping and reading order aligned with task sequence: task start, status, secondary action, help.\n- For lists and legal/settings screens, avoid unlabeled controls and dense icon-only actions unless supported by system conventions.\n- Where sound is used for success/error feedback, pair with non-audio confirmation paths to remain inclusive.\n\n## Notification And Interruption Guidance\n- Request notification permissions only in context and only after explaining why reminders/replies are useful for wake routines.\n- Use `UNUserNotificationCenter` authorization with only required options (`alert`, `sound`, `badge`) matching actual behavior.\n- Use alerts and notifications for meaningful interruption events, not purely informational updates that can be surfaced in-app.\n- Design for missed or delayed delivery as an edge case rather than failure; keep app state resilient when a reminder does not arrive.\n- Prefer action-based notification categories for high-value, response-oriented notifications; keep interaction choices small and legible.\n- Avoid repeated interruption patterns after each failure event; provide recovery controls in-app before suggesting another push.\n\n## Screen Type Implications\n- Onboarding: show concise purpose + optional path, allow exit/skip and resume, and avoid launching into rigid data collection.\n- Home: expose primary mission signal first (next wake action, active state), then secondary cards.\n- Primary_list (wake run list): prioritize row clarity and short status text, keep list scanning fast on first launch and under one-hand use.\n- Create_edit: stage form steps, validate progressively, keep save/confirm as the dominant action and support quick cancellation.\n- Active_task: treat as urgency state; show one clear control for mission action and clearly labeled recovery/finish path.\n- Completion: present success confirmation, emotional continuity, and optional replay/recover options without shaming.\n- History_streaks: explain metrics in plain language so users understand how streaks are computed and repaired.\n- Profile_settings: separate account/help/legal/support from mission controls; protect destructive actions with explicit confirmation.\n- Paywall_subscription: keep paywall presentation contextual and not as an interruption mid-mission; maintain transparent opt-out and restore paths.\n\n## what_to_adapt\n- Use system-first SwiftUI structures for navigation (`NavigationStack`, `List`, `TabView`) and keep customizations minimal.\n- Use explicit onboarding progression with optionality and short explanatory copy tied to immediate app actions.\n- Keep tab navigation at the top level and keep every tab icon/label singular and descriptive.\n- Use one dominant button style for the primary action and secondary styling for alternative options.\n- Add explicit accessibility labels/hints/values to custom controls and keep action feedback accessible in text.\n- Implement notification requests in a clearly-scoped prelude to reminder features, and align notification actions with wake mission outcomes.\n- Use motion for task status and completion feedback only; keep high-frequency animations short and interruptible.\n\n## what_not_to_copy\n- Do not copy closed-loop onboarding that blocks launch or requires full auth completion before value becomes visible.\n- Do not copy layouts where tab bars behave like action rails or change visibility unpredictably.\n- Do not copy alert-heavy patterns for non-critical flow messaging.\n- Do not copy dense equal-weight CTA sets during active wake and completion states.\n- Do not copy color-only status systems or tiny control targets that reduce operability with accessibility settings.\n- Do not copy repetitive interruption behavior (repeat alerts/push loops) after missed wake attempts.\n- Do not copy platform-incompatible wording or tone in destructive paths (especially in profile/legal account actions).\n- Do not copy inaccessible custom controls lacking SwiftUI accessibility annotations.\nEOF\"'","aggregated_output":"/bin/bash: line 1: MainTabView: command not found\n/bin/bash: line 1: Home: command not found\n/bin/bash: line 1: Runs: command not found\n/bin/bash: line 1: Profile: command not found\n/bin/bash: line 1: UNUserNotificationCenter: command not found\n/bin/bash: line 1: alert: command not found\n/bin/bash: line 1: sound: command not found\n/bin/bash: line 1: badge: command not found\n/bin/bash: line 1: NavigationStack: command not found\n/bin/bash: line 1: List: command not found\n/bin/bash: line 1: TabView: command not found\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
